  "body": "Is this a bug report or feature request?\r\n* Bug Report\r\n\r\n**Bug Report**\r\n\r\nWhat happened:\r\nI installed rook on one node with ~30 drives, and it failed on 16th. I did not record the error exactly, but it was complaining about hitting the limit of fs.aio-max-nr, which is equal to 65536 in CentOS 7.\r\nAfter that the OSD pod restarted and was never able to recover, complaining that the OSD folder already exists.\r\n\r\nWhat you expected to happen:\r\nrook should set this limit itself, or give a clear error and continue initializing OSDs after POD crash\r\n\r\nHow to reproduce it (minimal and precise):\r\ninstall minikube, init rook on system with multiple drives\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n* OS (e.g. from /etc/os-release):\r\nCentOS Linux 7\r\n* Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`):\r\nLinux sdsu-ceph-01.sdsu.edu 4.14.15-1.el7.elrepo.x86_64 #1 SMP Tue Jan 23 20:28:26 EST 2018 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux\r\n* Cloud provider or hardware configuration:\r\nbaremetal\r\n* Rook version (use `rook version` inside of a Rook Pod):\r\nv0.6.0-207.g516e96f\r\n* Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`):\r\n1.9.0\r\n* Kubernetes cluster type (e.g. Tectonic, GKE, OpenShift):\r\nminikube\r\n",
